00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:10.930
JENNY ARDEN: Hi, I'm Jenny.

00:00:10.930 --> 00:00:12.650
I'm a designer at Google.

00:00:12.650 --> 00:00:15.090
I work on the
self-driving car project.

00:00:15.090 --> 00:00:18.470
Before this project at Google,
I worked on YouTube for TV,

00:00:18.470 --> 00:00:21.400
designing TV-specific
experiences.

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:24.770
And I also worked on Google's
core business search.

00:00:24.770 --> 00:00:27.930
So before that, I had my
fair share of agency work,

00:00:27.930 --> 00:00:29.000
mostly in New York City.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.070
And I've started a couple
small businesses as well.

00:00:33.070 --> 00:00:35.170
So what I want to
talk about today

00:00:35.170 --> 00:00:37.990
is what it feels like to be
a creative person working

00:00:37.990 --> 00:00:40.880
on a project that has
no concrete definition

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:42.880
and has very little structure.

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:45.870
More specifically, I want to
talk about the emotional ups

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:49.020
and downs that creative-minded
people go through when they're

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:51.290
working on something
brand new, and how

00:00:51.290 --> 00:00:54.550
you can use those emotions
to be your North Star.

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:58.940
So to start out, I want you
to think back and recollect

00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:02.850
the first moment that you
had a truly creative moment

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:04.480
and recognized it.

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:07.330
For some of you, it may
have been a simple drawing.

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:09.970
And I think there are some
rock stars in this room

00:01:09.970 --> 00:01:12.530
probably had been
artistic since birth,

00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:16.080
so this shouldn't
be too hard for you.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:18.010
So this is mine.

00:01:18.010 --> 00:01:19.340
I drew this when I was three.

00:01:19.340 --> 00:01:22.560
And it hangs in the kitchen
of my house where I grew up.

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:24.400
My mom looks at it
every single day

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:27.050
when she makes
her cup of coffee.

00:01:27.050 --> 00:01:29.550
What I love about
this is it somehow

00:01:29.550 --> 00:01:32.880
captured life according
to my three-year-old eyes.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:34.094
You have my parents.

00:01:34.094 --> 00:01:35.010
My mom's on the right.

00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:36.270
She's kind of leaning back.

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:38.360
My dad's in the middle.

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:40.590
Then we have our old sofa.

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:42.650
We had this thing forever.

00:01:42.650 --> 00:01:44.690
And I used to play
with my toys on it.

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:47.390
And then on the left, in
a very abstracted way,

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:49.060
is a huge pile of books.

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:52.820
And we had piles and piles
of books in our house.

00:01:52.820 --> 00:01:56.280
What I like about this is that
somehow, this simple drawing,

00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:57.870
it accurately
represented everything

00:01:57.870 --> 00:02:00.790
that I had at that time.

00:02:00.790 --> 00:02:04.340
So for other people, their
first creative experience

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:06.240
may have been building a fort.

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:07.730
My mom is a
self-employed writer.

00:02:07.730 --> 00:02:10.910
So we used to get these
really insanely thick boxes

00:02:10.910 --> 00:02:12.060
full of her books.

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:15.330
And they were the ultimate
building material for kids.

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:19.500
So we would create these very
elaborate mazes and forts.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:21.860
And sometimes, especially
in our own bedrooms,

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:25.212
we would layer them,
kind of creating a three,

00:02:25.212 --> 00:02:27.210
four-story maze.

00:02:27.210 --> 00:02:29.170
And they were kind of
like a human ant farm.

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:35.390
So what we loved about
building these forts

00:02:35.390 --> 00:02:38.180
is that we made
something out of nothing.

00:02:38.180 --> 00:02:41.240
Somehow you can take something
as clean as cardboard

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:43.560
and make it interesting
and important.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:47.430
In this picture, this is an
architecture firm that I found.

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:48.860
They're called Nothing.

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:51.470
And their entire premise
is based off the idea

00:02:51.470 --> 00:02:54.226
that you can take something
very simple, a plot of land,

00:02:54.226 --> 00:02:55.600
something that
has nothing there,

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:58.470
and make something absolutely
beautiful out of it.

00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:00.990
Their office, the
interior of their office,

00:03:00.990 --> 00:03:03.420
is built entirely
out of cardboard,

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:06.450
and it's pretty elaborate.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:10.770
So despite all this creativity
that we have at an early age,

00:03:10.770 --> 00:03:12.640
something happens.

00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:15.160
Kids are fearless and
will show their art.

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:18.880
But as we get older, we're
less secure with our confidence

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.350
and our own creativity.

00:03:21.350 --> 00:03:24.440
The door starts to
close, and many designers

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.452
keep their work locked away
until they think it's perfect,

00:03:28.452 --> 00:03:30.160
or until they have a
deadline and they're

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:32.800
forced to show it to their team.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.810
We start to fear judgment.

00:03:34.810 --> 00:03:38.350
We fear judgment from
our peers, and we

00:03:38.350 --> 00:03:40.700
fear that we're going
to be embarrassed.

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:43.760
How many times have you looked
over a designer's shoulder

00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:46.930
to see their work in progress,
and their actual posture

00:03:46.930 --> 00:03:48.320
starts to change?

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:51.850
They start to recoil, and their
voice sounds apprehensive.

00:03:51.850 --> 00:03:54.020
And they give you
this doe-eyed look

00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:55.850
that they just fear
that you're going

00:03:55.850 --> 00:03:57.320
to say it's going to suck.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:00.310
That is their worst nightmare.

00:04:00.310 --> 00:04:02.360
So why is this?

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:06.150
Part of our DNA, the fact
that we are designers,

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:11.250
we have built into our
DNA the essence of taste.

00:04:11.250 --> 00:04:14.460
Being a great designer
is to have good taste

00:04:14.460 --> 00:04:16.730
and to know what good
taste looks like.

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:20.140
This means we love beauty,
and invention, and things

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:21.560
that surprise us.

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:23.460
We fall in love
with great design.

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:25.700
But we also want to
produce that great design

00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:28.500
and have an effect
on other people.

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:30.660
But as we face this
big blank page,

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:32.680
whether that's your
sketch book or Photoshop

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:36.150
or whatever tool you use,
and start to design away,

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:38.840
our craft doesn't
always meet our taste.

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:40.630
And it's especially
in the beginning

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:42.880
of a designer's career
this is very true.

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:44.550
So sometimes our
fear of judgment

00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:48.480
is actually knowing for a fact
that the design we've created

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.510
is not nearly as good
as we want it to be,

00:04:50.510 --> 00:04:54.070
and we're about to
be called out on it.

00:04:54.070 --> 00:04:57.440
So let's layer on top of
that those moments when

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:00.620
you work on a project
that's truly innovative.

00:05:00.620 --> 00:05:03.080
I've been working on the
self-driving car, which

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:05.890
is pretty innovative, so I've
been living and breathing

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:09.410
this uncharted territory
for quite a while.

00:05:09.410 --> 00:05:12.160
Now you're this designer
that wants to create,

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:15.470
and you're swimming
in this abyss.

00:05:15.470 --> 00:05:18.040
You're in this space
of uncertainty.

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:20.240
You want to grab at all
the tangible aspects

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:21.880
and make something out of it.

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:24.360
And you don't have
all the answers yet.

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:26.570
So in the back of
your head, you know

00:05:26.570 --> 00:05:28.770
that you want to make
something great as a designer.

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:30.150
You're working with
a project that you

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:31.608
don't have all the
definitions for.

00:05:31.608 --> 00:05:34.260
And you want to make it awesome.

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:36.480
So what does this mean?

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:39.300
For those that can
relate, definitely

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:42.003
the entrepreneurs and
inventors in this room,

00:05:42.003 --> 00:05:46.206
you know that being in this
spot can be a very lonely place.

00:05:46.206 --> 00:05:47.830
It's especially
interesting when you're

00:05:47.830 --> 00:05:51.300
surrounded by nondesigners,
and they're all looking at you

00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:54.550
to come up with a solution
because you're the creative.

00:05:54.550 --> 00:05:57.340
For your coworkers that haven't
been on a project like this

00:05:57.340 --> 00:06:00.680
before, they make the
project look like this.

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:02.300
And they may think
it looks like this,

00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:06.280
where it has a
beginning and an end.

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:07.390
The reality?

00:06:07.390 --> 00:06:09.860
Experience is a lot like this.

00:06:09.860 --> 00:06:13.090
For those who are confused,
this is Tough Mudder.

00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:16.280
This race is full of
obstacles, and scary hazards,

00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:18.010
and barbed wire,
and contraptions

00:06:18.010 --> 00:06:19.940
that will electrocute you.

00:06:19.940 --> 00:06:22.910
It's pretty crazy,
and people pay for it.

00:06:22.910 --> 00:06:25.550
It's messy, and it's
ugly, and you're not

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:27.270
sure you're going to finish.

00:06:27.270 --> 00:06:30.670
So what's interesting is that
it's less about the individual,

00:06:30.670 --> 00:06:32.540
and it's more about
the team effort.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:36.150
Everyone has to help
everyone to finish.

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:40.440
I can say for a fact that I've
been on three projects that

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:42.650
have definitely felt like this.

00:06:42.650 --> 00:06:45.400
And I'm going to walk you
through two of them today.

00:06:45.400 --> 00:06:48.910
Several years ago, when I
was working in New York City,

00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:51.800
I was working with an
agency called Razorfish.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:53.540
You might have heard of it.

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:55.970
And this is a project
that was really

00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:59.140
based on business innovation.

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.380
So a small team
of us were tasked

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:03.430
with creating a really
interesting dashboard

00:07:03.430 --> 00:07:05.420
for the United Nations.

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:07.340
This project was
focused specifically

00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:10.780
on economic
development in Africa.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:13.680
For 12 years,
representatives from the UN

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:15.640
went door to door
to small businesses

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:19.300
throughout the continent
and interviewed the owners.

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:24.960
They would ask questions
like, was tax rate reasonable?

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:27.970
Did you have to use a
bribe to get business done?

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:30.930
Were you able to find
educated workers?

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:33.415
Did you have reliable
access to electricity

00:07:33.415 --> 00:07:37.900
and water-- some pretty
basic things to do business.

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:42.260
So hundreds and hundreds of
questions-- again, 12 years.

00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:46.039
They had this massive database,
this huge spreadsheet.

00:07:46.039 --> 00:07:47.830
And all the answers
were collected verbally

00:07:47.830 --> 00:07:52.300
and then compiled into this
database, mostly a huge Excel

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:54.170
spreadsheet.

00:07:54.170 --> 00:07:55.400
And this was a lot of work.

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:57.100
I mean, 12 years
is a lot of work.

00:07:57.100 --> 00:07:59.420
So why did they do this?

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:00.730
They had a vision.

00:08:00.730 --> 00:08:03.060
And they thought if they
can collect this data,

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:05.460
they can reveal to
foreign investors

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:08.220
which countries were
doing fair business

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:11.380
and which countries were
actually very corrupt.

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:13.120
This was a very important time.

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:15.090
Many large companies
were looking at Africa

00:08:15.090 --> 00:08:17.340
as the next big emerging market.

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:19.980
The cost of business
in India and China,

00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:21.050
it was already rising.

00:08:21.050 --> 00:08:24.280
So Africa was seen as the next
step for companies seeking

00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:26.690
alternative low-cost solutions.

00:08:26.690 --> 00:08:29.280
This dashboard that we
created, this was a prototype.

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:31.800
This was just a rough design.

00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:34.900
It really represented
the parsing of the data

00:08:34.900 --> 00:08:37.490
and allowed for quick
custom filtering,

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:39.799
display visualization,
and revealed

00:08:39.799 --> 00:08:41.590
the countries that were
doing fair business

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:45.140
and the countries that
had corrupt practices

00:08:45.140 --> 00:08:46.320
in a real and tangible way.

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:48.540
They could actually see it.

00:08:48.540 --> 00:08:53.700
So three months later, to my
surprise, I am now in Ethiopia.

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:55.180
And I have to present this.

00:08:55.180 --> 00:08:58.365
Never been to the continent of
Africa, definitely never been

00:08:58.365 --> 00:09:01.670
to Ethiopia-- very cool
place, very vibrant,

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:03.590
full of color and life.

00:09:03.590 --> 00:09:06.010
And I found myself
presenting these designs

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:09.710
to diplomats, and ministers,
and African leaders seated

00:09:09.710 --> 00:09:12.920
in a very traditional UN setup.

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:16.100
If you've ever seen
pictures of it or on TV,

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:18.260
it feels very official.

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:19.900
Each person sits at their desk.

00:09:19.900 --> 00:09:20.910
They have their placard.

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:23.150
They have their translator
with a microphone.

00:09:23.150 --> 00:09:26.300
They have titles like
Kenyan Minister of Mines,

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:27.790
which I did not know existed.

00:09:27.790 --> 00:09:31.500
And all of these diplomats
were there to listen to us

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.510
and to see our solution.

00:09:33.510 --> 00:09:36.950
To be honest, I was
absolutely terrified.

00:09:36.950 --> 00:09:39.390
There was not a single
designer in that room.

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:42.620
And they were all
definitely official looking.

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:45.190
But what helped us
more than anything

00:09:45.190 --> 00:09:48.720
was believing that the actual
solution that we'd created

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:51.340
solved the problem.

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:54.810
But what was also scary
was that the solution

00:09:54.810 --> 00:09:57.120
was incredibly polarizing.

00:09:57.120 --> 00:09:59.150
So we gave this
presentation, and we

00:09:59.150 --> 00:10:01.140
get two types of feedback.

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:02.940
Naturally, those
representatives from

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:06.420
business-friendly
countries were psyched.

00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:10.600
We're now finally rewarding
them for doing good business.

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:13.270
But those other
countries, those countries

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:16.490
that maybe had not
so favorable scores,

00:10:16.490 --> 00:10:18.080
they were pretty
pissed off at us.

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:21.650
And that was a
difficult situation

00:10:21.650 --> 00:10:25.600
to be in when you're
trying to present that.

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:28.970
So the takeaway from
that is that when

00:10:28.970 --> 00:10:31.200
you're working on something
that can fundamentally

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:33.790
change how we
think of a problem,

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:37.250
it's very likely that you're
going to make a lot of friends.

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:39.835
But you can also
make some enemies,

00:10:39.835 --> 00:10:41.780
and you'll have some naysayers.

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:45.620
I think Airbnb and Uber probably
experienced some of this.

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:47.900
They kind of know what
we're talking about.

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:51.850
And the self-driving car, we
deal with some of this as well.

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:54.320
The design may not have
been revolutionary.

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:56.530
Data dashboards are not special.

00:10:56.530 --> 00:11:00.190
But the use of that
design had a huge impact.

00:11:00.190 --> 00:11:02.050
In this case, we
were potentially

00:11:02.050 --> 00:11:05.610
affecting the business landscape
of an entire continent, which

00:11:05.610 --> 00:11:08.200
is a huge thing.

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:10.180
Now let's talk about
the self-driving car.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:11.800
This is the next
project that I'd

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:15.260
say I was in kind of a
Tough Mudder situation.

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:18.910
On this project, I'm
reminded every single day

00:11:18.910 --> 00:11:21.080
that we're solving a
computer science problem.

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:23.270
Now mind you, when I
came onto the project,

00:11:23.270 --> 00:11:25.500
I had no automotive
background whatsoever.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:27.097
I am a user experience designer.

00:11:27.097 --> 00:11:29.430
I try to actually get to the
heart of what people really

00:11:29.430 --> 00:11:30.780
want.

00:11:30.780 --> 00:11:33.890
So as a designer,
I'm reminded why

00:11:33.890 --> 00:11:35.940
we're doing this
in the first place.

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:38.160
I'm motivated by how
the project can actually

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:43.570
change lives, and communities,
and landscapes in a real way.

00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:47.470
I'm motivated by the idea
that we are all bad drivers

00:11:47.470 --> 00:11:49.250
if we want to admit it or not.

00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:50.400
We text.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:51.640
We read emails.

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:54.000
I've seen people put
makeup on while driving.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.690
I saw a guy eating a bowl
of soup while driving.

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:02.210
This is actually truly
dangerous, life-threatening

00:12:02.210 --> 00:12:03.770
behavior that we are conducting.

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:06.420
And we just do it because
it's always that chance

00:12:06.420 --> 00:12:07.300
that it's not me.

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:10.410
I'm not the one that's
going to cause the problem.

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:14.450
So diving a bit deeper
into the project,

00:12:14.450 --> 00:12:17.800
we can talk about the lasers,
and the radars, and the map

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:19.800
tiles, and the latency.

