00:20:59.350 --> 00:21:03.440
So what I wanted to
sort of bring together

00:21:03.440 --> 00:21:06.460
is my thoughts about
emotions and when

00:21:06.460 --> 00:21:08.280
you're working on
these projects.

00:21:08.280 --> 00:21:12.320
So for those that live
and breathe 10X concepts,

00:21:12.320 --> 00:21:15.670
meaning ideas that improve
problems by 10 times,

00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:17.610
I truly believe
that your emotions

00:21:17.610 --> 00:21:19.310
can be your North Star.

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:25.920
So anxiety, for example--
it's not always a bad thing.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:27.770
Medically, it increases
your blood flow.

00:21:27.770 --> 00:21:30.200
It releases hormones
like adrenaline.

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:32.820
It allows your mind
to work on overdrive.

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:35.080
For those procrastinators
in the room--

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:39.240
I am one of them-- your
work can feel better

00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:41.510
when you wait till
the last minute.

00:21:41.510 --> 00:21:45.710
Sometimes that pressure to
produce just makes better work.

00:21:45.710 --> 00:21:47.850
But for a lot of
people, anxiety is

00:21:47.850 --> 00:21:50.600
felt because you
don't have a plan.

00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:52.900
So I think it's
important to note

00:21:52.900 --> 00:21:55.990
that you can't plan innovation.

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:57.770
You can have these
big ideas, and you

00:21:57.770 --> 00:22:00.200
have an idea where
it's going to,

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:04.920
but there really is no concrete
roadmap for innovation.

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:06.906
I once heard the
creator of Radiolab,

00:22:06.906 --> 00:22:08.280
which is by far
my favorite radio

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:10.690
show-- I absolutely
love that show.

00:22:10.690 --> 00:22:13.260
And he's won great
awards for basically

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:15.670
changing the format of radio.

00:22:15.670 --> 00:22:17.900
He said, "I don't think
change can be planned.

00:22:17.900 --> 00:22:19.400
I think it's only
something that can

00:22:19.400 --> 00:22:20.805
be recognized after the fact."

00:22:20.805 --> 00:22:22.180
And I absolutely
agree with this.

00:22:22.180 --> 00:22:24.099
And the two projects I
shared with you today,

00:22:24.099 --> 00:22:26.390
I think it's absolutely--
we're obviously still working

00:22:26.390 --> 00:22:27.470
on the self-driving car.

00:22:27.470 --> 00:22:29.210
But we're definitely
feeling this.

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:35.080
So you can have a plan,
especially for the next couple

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:37.920
weeks, but expect that
it will change a lot.

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:41.170
Because there's a lot
you just don't know.

00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:43.940
The real challenge is
to be OK with that,

00:22:43.940 --> 00:22:46.830
and to recognize that
your anxiety is usually

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:49.780
a sign that you're either
going to figure something out,

00:22:49.780 --> 00:22:52.570
you're about to get there, or
the plan is about to change.

00:22:52.570 --> 00:22:55.360
It's one of the two.

00:22:55.360 --> 00:23:00.490
So for those moments that you
experience fear with your work,

00:23:00.490 --> 00:23:02.810
know that fear is usually
a sign that you're

00:23:02.810 --> 00:23:04.240
working on something brand new.

00:23:04.240 --> 00:23:06.990
And that's a pretty lucky
place to be as a designer.

00:23:06.990 --> 00:23:12.300
This is a rare, rare
occasion, so be grateful.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:15.750
But you may be a new
designer learning your craft.

00:23:15.750 --> 00:23:17.877
That is also a scary place.

00:23:17.877 --> 00:23:19.710
And you're trying things
for the first time.

00:23:19.710 --> 00:23:20.940
Or you may be
working on something

00:23:20.940 --> 00:23:22.023
like the self-driving car.

00:23:22.023 --> 00:23:23.840
It kind of feels the same.

00:23:23.840 --> 00:23:26.130
Either way, you're
diving into the unknown.

00:23:26.130 --> 00:23:28.250
And you will learn from it.

00:23:28.250 --> 00:23:30.820
If you're feeling
comfortable, chances

00:23:30.820 --> 00:23:33.760
are you either found a
bit of clarity and maybe

00:23:33.760 --> 00:23:37.270
a few answers, or maybe you've
relied on something safe

00:23:37.270 --> 00:23:39.670
and maybe already done.

00:23:39.670 --> 00:23:41.190
That's not necessarily
a bad thing.

00:23:41.190 --> 00:23:43.140
But please make sure
that you're doing it

00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:44.980
because it's a
better experience,

00:23:44.980 --> 00:23:48.100
not because it's easier.

00:23:48.100 --> 00:23:50.610
And this is my last
major point here.

00:23:50.610 --> 00:23:52.850
If you are experiencing
a moment of joy,

00:23:52.850 --> 00:23:54.720
those moments where
you're like, I freaking

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:58.124
did that-- and we've all kind
of had either little moments

00:23:58.124 --> 00:24:00.040
of that, or big ones
where there was a launch,

00:24:00.040 --> 00:24:01.540
or you just showed
up for a meeting,

00:24:01.540 --> 00:24:04.050
and you were really actually
proud of that design--

00:24:04.050 --> 00:24:05.840
take the time to celebrate.

00:24:05.840 --> 00:24:08.880
More often, I see so
many designers run out

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:11.319
of drive and creativity
because they're pushing

00:24:11.319 --> 00:24:13.360
and they're fighting to
get to those moments that

00:24:13.360 --> 00:24:14.620
reveal answers.

00:24:14.620 --> 00:24:17.430
And they just start to burn out.

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:19.480
And I really think
small celebrations

00:24:19.480 --> 00:24:21.800
throughout your process will
save you from burning out,

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:23.990
especially when you're
working on a very

00:24:23.990 --> 00:24:27.310
long-term innovative project
like the self-driving car.

00:24:27.310 --> 00:24:29.520
So feel love for design.

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:31.140
That will keep you going.

00:24:31.140 --> 00:24:34.160
Be grateful that you have
the power and privilege

00:24:34.160 --> 00:24:37.170
to make something meaningful.

00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:38.680
And that's it for me.

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:39.730
Any questions?

00:24:39.730 --> 00:24:43.870
I'd love to answer
any questions I can.

00:24:43.870 --> 00:24:45.370
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:45.370 --> 00:24:46.520
Thank you.

00:24:51.810 --> 00:24:55.420
DIEGO: Hi, I'm Diego, and I'm
a designer and researcher.

00:24:55.420 --> 00:24:58.265
I was wondering if
you could tell us--

00:24:58.265 --> 00:25:03.040
and I don't know if you can--
how do you quickly validate

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:05.860
some of the assumptions
that you're working on?

00:25:05.860 --> 00:25:09.150
It seems like there's a pretty
significant prototype you're

00:25:09.150 --> 00:25:13.770
playing with, with the car and
the interface working together.

00:25:13.770 --> 00:25:16.930
JENNY ARDEN: Yeah, so I'd
say that our project is

00:25:16.930 --> 00:25:18.680
divided into two components.

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:20.390
So there's industrial design.

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:22.870
And luckily, with
building a car,

00:25:22.870 --> 00:25:24.430
there is some
precedence to that.

00:25:24.430 --> 00:25:25.690
And there's some
people actually here

00:25:25.690 --> 00:25:27.689
that know about that
process way more than I do,

00:25:27.689 --> 00:25:29.300
because I didn't
come from automotive.

00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:31.383
So they're kind of roughly
following this process.

00:25:31.383 --> 00:25:34.720
But like I was
kind of explaining,

00:25:34.720 --> 00:25:36.450
they course-correct a lot.

00:25:36.450 --> 00:25:40.830
And they are all willing to kind
of deal with change and deal

00:25:40.830 --> 00:25:43.120
with limitations that
they're faced with.

00:25:43.120 --> 00:25:45.644
So it's almost more of an
attitude than a process.

00:25:45.644 --> 00:25:47.060
They have a process,
but they also

00:25:47.060 --> 00:25:49.160
have the attitude
to accept change.

00:25:49.160 --> 00:25:53.274
On the digital side, we
have two major components

00:25:53.274 --> 00:25:54.190
that we're working on.

00:25:54.190 --> 00:25:58.060
It's the phone app,
the control of the car.

00:25:58.060 --> 00:26:01.750
And we have this kind of
crazy screen in the prototype.

00:26:01.750 --> 00:26:03.330
It's long and
skinny, and it sits

00:26:03.330 --> 00:26:05.740
about four feet from the eye.

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:07.950
That's the one that is
more difficult for us.

00:26:07.950 --> 00:26:11.550
We can design a phone app pretty
easily to control the car.

00:26:11.550 --> 00:26:14.080
But that UI and the
engineering interface

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:16.700
that I shared with you,
it's pretty gnarly.

00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:21.710
So basically what we do is
we just try everything out.

00:26:21.710 --> 00:26:23.320
Everything is a hypothesis.

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:25.600
And we get into the prototype.

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:27.640
If you don't experience
it firsthand,

00:26:27.640 --> 00:26:29.420
if it's just at your
computer, you're

00:26:29.420 --> 00:26:31.560
never going to
get a real answer.

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:34.300
So we really believe in
taking it out in the field

00:26:34.300 --> 00:26:36.910
and experiencing it firsthand
and getting a gut check

00:26:36.910 --> 00:26:37.500
with it.

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:39.860
And then obviously, the
next step after that

00:26:39.860 --> 00:26:41.990
is testing with real users.

00:26:41.990 --> 00:26:44.490
So we've identified
user groups that we

00:26:44.490 --> 00:26:46.330
want to really get
their feedback from.

00:26:46.330 --> 00:26:48.413
We put it in front of them
and get their insights.

00:26:48.413 --> 00:26:50.640
And we just keep going
and going and going.

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:54.300
This is not sort of
a waterfall effect.

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:57.730
My researchers are next
to me every single day

00:26:57.730 --> 00:26:58.600
testing things.

00:27:01.410 --> 00:27:02.390
AUDIENCE: I'm curious.

00:27:02.390 --> 00:27:05.230
You're a user experience
designer, correct?

00:27:05.230 --> 00:27:09.250
I'd love to know more about the
experience you're aiming for.

00:27:09.250 --> 00:27:11.503
Because it seems so broad,
and everyone in the video

00:27:11.503 --> 00:27:13.862
is either-- not disabled.

00:27:13.862 --> 00:27:14.570
Everyone's happy.

00:27:14.570 --> 00:27:16.069
And everybody's
having a great time.

00:27:16.069 --> 00:27:18.240
And I'm curious.

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:21.730
Are you striving for
collaboration and communication

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:24.040
between passengers?

00:27:24.040 --> 00:27:26.540
I just am a little more
curious about the specifics

00:27:26.540 --> 00:27:28.124
of that goal.

00:27:28.124 --> 00:27:30.290
JENNY ARDEN: Yep, so I
agree, everyone in that video

00:27:30.290 --> 00:27:32.040
did look very happy,
unnaturally so.

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:33.540
But they actually
were really happy.

00:27:33.540 --> 00:27:36.160
It was a good day for us.

00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:39.590
The experience, I'd say we have
different feelings about it

00:27:39.590 --> 00:27:42.860
depending on when you're
thinking about the project

00:27:42.860 --> 00:27:43.860
and how far along it is.

00:27:43.860 --> 00:27:49.870
So when we release it
to the world, which

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:53.960
will happen one day, we're
just trying to get trust.

00:27:53.960 --> 00:27:57.140
We just want people to feel
safe and really trust it.

00:27:57.140 --> 00:28:00.310
And we will not launch anything
that isn't absolutely safe.

00:28:00.310 --> 00:28:05.720
We have very, very high bars
for all of our safety metrics.

00:28:05.720 --> 00:28:09.670
So safety, trust-- number one.

00:28:09.670 --> 00:28:13.310
Friendly-- no scary robots.

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:17.450
That's really important to
us as a user experience team.

00:28:17.450 --> 00:28:20.500
Further out, though,
the feeling that we have

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:23.600
is that we can actually change
some really interesting aspects

00:28:23.600 --> 00:28:25.120
about society.

00:28:25.120 --> 00:28:27.240
Think about it-- you get
your driver's license

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:30.130
as a rite of passage
when you're 16-ish.

00:28:30.130 --> 00:28:31.840
What if that doesn't
exist anymore?

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:33.030
That's kind of crazy.

00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:34.110
There's a fly over here.

00:28:34.110 --> 00:28:35.480
That's kind of crazy.

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:41.120
So what is the new rite
of passage for driving?

00:28:41.120 --> 00:28:43.640
There are lots of things
culturally in our DNA

00:28:43.640 --> 00:28:46.410
about driving,
especially in California.

00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:49.660
We care so much about driving.

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:51.490
How is this project
going to change that?

00:28:51.490 --> 00:28:54.729
And those are the things that
we're thinking about a lot.

00:28:54.729 --> 00:28:55.270
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:28:55.270 --> 00:28:59.690
Have you done any explorations
of more nontraditional spaces

00:28:59.690 --> 00:29:01.950
within the car,
thinking about it

00:29:01.950 --> 00:29:04.900
not just as a place for seats,
but as a place for a desk,

00:29:04.900 --> 00:29:08.940
as a place for an
exercise bike, as a place

00:29:08.940 --> 00:29:11.560
to accomplish other goals while
you are being transported?

00:29:11.560 --> 00:29:12.560
JENNY ARDEN: Absolutely.

00:29:12.560 --> 00:29:17.410
So one of the questions I posed
was, what is the new driving?

00:29:17.410 --> 00:29:19.700
If you're not driving,
you're doing something else.

00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:21.700
So if you're doing something
else, what is that,

00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:24.760
and how can the space
enable that other activity?

00:29:24.760 --> 00:29:26.660
So could we enable working?

00:29:26.660 --> 00:29:28.980
Could we enable conversations?

00:29:28.980 --> 00:29:33.030
Maybe enable productivity,
or just relaxation-- you just

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:37.420
want to unplug and
sit back and relax.

00:29:37.420 --> 00:29:39.410
As a user experience
team, these are definitely

00:29:39.410 --> 00:29:41.959
the things we're thinking
about, and thinking

00:29:41.959 --> 00:29:43.500
about how the interior
of the vehicle

00:29:43.500 --> 00:29:45.190
itself can be
configured or changed.

00:29:45.190 --> 00:29:48.310
Or we can design
something to really cater

00:29:48.310 --> 00:29:50.614
toward one of those experiences.

00:29:50.614 --> 00:29:52.030
AUDIENCE: Now that
you're spending

00:29:52.030 --> 00:29:54.300
so much time in
self-driving cars,

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:56.775
would you say that it's
made driving in your car

00:29:56.775 --> 00:29:59.599
or driving around
more or less fun?

00:29:59.599 --> 00:30:01.140
JENNY ARDEN: So I
actually hate cars.

00:30:01.140 --> 00:30:02.431
I'm going to be totally honest.

00:30:02.431 --> 00:30:03.440
I'm a cyclist.

00:30:03.440 --> 00:30:04.976
I don't like cars.

00:30:04.976 --> 00:30:06.600
So it's funny that
I'm on this project.

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:11.470
But it's actually great, because
I believe in a different thing.

00:30:11.470 --> 00:30:15.300
I believe that there's a
place for cars, especially

00:30:15.300 --> 00:30:17.560
the joy riding when
you love vehicles

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:20.570
and you love the machinery
and the engineering.

00:30:20.570 --> 00:30:22.920
There are plenty of people
on my team who are like that.

00:30:22.920 --> 00:30:25.020
And I respect all
of their hobbies

00:30:25.020 --> 00:30:26.870
and their passion for it.

00:30:26.870 --> 00:30:30.960
But for me, I'd say
that I am already

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:34.410
someone who was kind
of on the other side.

00:30:34.410 --> 00:30:36.680
In college, I was
in a major accident.

00:30:36.680 --> 00:30:40.460
And I had post-traumatic
stress from it,

00:30:40.460 --> 00:30:43.280
so I couldn't actually get
into a car for about a year.

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:45.210
I had to walk or ride my bike.

00:30:45.210 --> 00:30:47.340
That's why I became
a cyclist, because I

00:30:47.340 --> 00:30:48.960
was so terrified
to get into a car.

00:30:48.960 --> 00:30:53.570
So I already, in my
depths of my being,

00:30:53.570 --> 00:30:56.860
really feel that this
is a necessary thing.

00:30:56.860 --> 00:30:59.100
OK, thank you, guys.

00:30:59.100 --> 00:31:01.850
[APPLAUSE]

